{"title_page": "La Chica Dorada", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = La Chica Dorada\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Paulina Rubio]]\n| cover      = PAU El tiempo es oro`.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1992|10|20|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = December 1991&nbsp;\u2013 February 1992\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Balu-Balu Estudios<br />([[Madrid]], [[Spain]])\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Latin pop]]|[[dance pop]]}}\n| length     = 37:59\n| label      = [[Capitol Latin]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Miguel Blasco]]|[[J.R. Florez]]}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[24 Kilates]]\n| next_year  = 1993\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = La Chica Dorada\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[M\u00edo]]\n | single1date = {{Start date|1992|8|30|mf=y}}\n | single2     = [[Abriendo las Puertas al Amor|Abriendo Las Puertas Al Amor]]\n | single2date = {{Start date|1993|2|20|mf=y}}\n | single3     = [[Amor de Mujer|Amor De Mujer]]\n | single3date = {{Start date|1993|5|29|mf=y}}\n | single4     = [[Sabor a Miel|Sabor A Miel]]\n | single4date = {{Start date|1993|8|12|mf=y}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''La Chica Dorada''''' (English: ''The Golden Girl'') is the solo debut studio album by Mexican pop singer [[Paulina Rubio]] (after leaving the [[Timbiriche]] group) and her first album by the [[EMI Latin]] record label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paulinarubio.com/site/listDiscography/xn/Discografia/_lang/es_ES/id/7/title/la-chica-dorada|title=Paulina Rubio Official Website: Discography -La Chica Dorada|publisher=paulinarubio.com|year=2012|accessdate=February 16, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426091110/http://www.paulinarubio.com/site/listDiscography/xn/Discografia/_lang/es_ES/id/7/title/la-chica-dorada|archivedate=April 26, 2012}}</ref> The album was produced and directed by [[Miguel Blasco]], and written mostly by [[J.R. Florez]], [[Gian Pietro Felisatti]] and Cesar Valle. Most of the composition of the album is [[dance-pop]], although it includes some elements of [[rock pop]], [[new jack swing]], [[new wave]] and [[funk]].\n\nThe album has received a mixed review from music critics; Many medios applauded the album itself for interesting themes and her step in the music industry as \"the girl to woman\", while some did not like another \"[[Madonna wannabe]]\" because of the great influence of the [[Madonna (entertainer)|North American artist]] on the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/cultura/paulina-rubio-dice-que-es-un-orgullo-que-la-califiquen-como-la-madonna/2001-09-09/105000.html|title=Paulina Rubio dice que es un orgullo que la califiquen como la \"Madonna latina\"|publisher=|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref> Despite the mixed critical reaction, ''La Chica Dorada'' was a worldwide success. The album includes Rubio's [[signature song]] and the single that launched her solo career, \"[[Mio (Paulina Rubio Song)|M\u00edo]]\", along with the number one hit singles \"[[Sabor a Miel|Sabor A Miel]]\" and \"[[Amor de Mujer|Amor De Mujer]]\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Paulina Rubio conducir\u00e1 ceremonia de MTV Video Music Awards |url=https://hoy.com.do/paulina-rubio-conducira-ceremonia-de-mtv-video-music-awards/ |website=hoydigital.do |publisher=Hoy Digital |accessdate=8 October 2019 |date=15 September 2004}}</ref> The album's title has stuck and today Rubio is known as 'la chica dorada' (the golden girl) and throughout the Spanish-speaking world. In Mexico, it was certifield platinum and three times gold in the 90s<ref name=\"PRlcdP\">{{cite web |title=Hit Parade |url=http://h.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Search&Key=EDT/1993/03/02/43/Ar04300.xml&CollName=EDT_1990_1999&DOCID=1226315&PageLabelPrint=43&skin=ElSiglo&AppName=2&sLanguage=English&Content=ALL&selLanguage=&sPublication=EDT&sDateFrom=01/01/1993&sDateTo=12/31/1993&dummy=1993&sQuery=paulina+rubio+platino&x=0&y=0&ViewMode=GIF |date=March 2, 1993 |accessdate=November 2, 2019 |work=[[El Siglo de Torre\u00f3n]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102165853/http://h.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Search&Key=EDT%2F1993%2F03%2F02%2F43%2FAr04300.xml&CollName=EDT_1990_1999&DOCID=1226315&PageLabelPrint=43&skin=ElSiglo&AppName=2&sLanguage=English&Content=ALL&selLanguage=&sPublication=EDT&sDateFrom=01%2F01%2F1993&sDateTo=12%2F31%2F1993&dummy=1993&sQuery=paulina+rubio+platino&x=0&y=0&ViewMode=GIF |archivedate=November 2, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and sold over 600,000 copies.<ref name=\"sixhundred\"/>\n\nIn the [[United States]], ''La Chica Dorada'' peaked at No. 42 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Top Latin Albums]] and sold 100,000 copies. The singles \"M\u00edo\", \"Amor De Mujer\" and \"[[Abriendo las puertas al amor|Abriendo Las Puertas Al Amor]]\" entered the Top 10 of [[Hot Latin Tracks]], turning Paulina Rubio into a strong promise of Hispanic music,<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0w8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA85&dq=paulina+rubio+la+chica+dorada&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiB8eyDjPXdAhVFIqwKHbBoCGYQ6AEILjAB#v=onepage&q=paulina%20rubio%20la%20chica%20dorada&f=false |title=Magic's In The Music And The Music's In These |publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=March 13, 1993|language=|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref> and the first Mexican artist who managed to enter the most important list of the music industry with her debut album, after the first releases of [[Ana Gabriel]], who had great success on the ''Billboard Latin'' charts.\n\n==Background and development==\n{{Quote box|width=300px|bgcolor=#cd9c3a|align=left|quote=\"For me the gold are memories: the golden years of rock and roll and cinema.\"|source=\u2014Rubio talking about the name of the album.\n}}\nAfter having been part of the [[Timbiriche]] group and recording ten studio albums, Rubio traveled to Europe in 1991 to study History of Art, but his greatest wish was to start his solo career. This is how [[Gian Pietro Felisatti]], better known as \"DiFelisatti\", one of the most outstanding composers of that era, along with [[Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n Fl\u00f3rez]], volunteered to work on the solo project of the young artist of 20 years. The well-known producers and she had a very good relationship, since both writers were responsible for great successes of the band Timbiriche. Added to the above, Rubio was established in Spain to start recordings of what would be his debut album.\n\n[[Miguel Blasco]], Spanish producer of the greatest discographic hits of [[Alejandra Guzm\u00e1n]], [[Yuri (Mexican singer)|Yuri]] and [[Mijares]] would handle all the production of La Chica Dorada, achieving a breakthrough in just four months of work. In June 1992, Paulina Rubio officially signed a contract with the [[EMI Latin|EMI Capitol]] label in Mexico<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubfansite.com/paulinarubio/biografia.php|title=Paulina Rubio, Biography|publisher=Fan site|year=1995|language=Spanish|accessdate=April 14, 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414145859/http://www.clubfansite.com/paulinarubio/biografia.php|archivedate=April 14, 2019}}</ref> and the song \"La Chica Dorada\" was released exclusively to publicize her solo project. The song describes the moments Rubio lived in Spain while studying Art History and dreamed of becoming a Hispanic pop star.\n\n==Released and promotion==\n[[File:EroticaGirlieShowUnderGround sh (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|\"La Chica Dorada\" was released the same day that [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], one of her biggest influences, published her album \"[[Erotica (Madonna album)|Erotica]]\".]]\n\nPrior to the promotion of the album, Rubio gave several details of his solo debut while he was recording the last scenes of the telenovela ''[[Baila conmigo (TV series)|Baila conmigo]]'', informing the media of his great radical change of image. ''La Chica Dorada'' was released in Mexico and United States on October 20, 1992, the same day that Madonna released her fifth studio album, ''[[Erotica (Madonna album)|Erotica]]''. The album was re-released in [[Europe]] in 2001, and the digital edition was released in 2005.\n\nThe promotion began in July 1992, when Rubio conducted a small advertising campaign by several Mexican media outlets, where she presented her new image as \"golden girl\" and promoted the song \"La Chica Dorada\" on some radio stations. \" The singer made several promotional appearances, including talk shows and live performances in the main cities of Mexico. Paulina Rubio made her debut as a solo singer on the legendary Mexican television program [[Siempre en Domingo]], with [[Ra\u00fal Velasco]] on October 18, 1992,<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1612204/ |title=Debut de Paulina Rubio como solista  |work=[[IMDb]] |year=2012|language=english |accessdate=October 12, 2018}}</ref> 3 days before her album was released. She performed the song \"Amor De Mujer\" and her first single, \"M\u00edo\". The famous television host commented that \"it was a great privilege to have presented Paulina as a solo singer\". His presentation had a high audience rating that the next week was invited again.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TZ9oz49bSuw |title=Paulina Rubio debut como solista en Siempre en Domingo |work=[[YouTube]] |year=2015|language=spanish|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref> In United States, for the Spanish-language television program [[S\u00e1bado Gigante]], Rubio performed the track \"M\u00edo\" in January, 1993 and that presentation opened the doors to the Hispanic market in that country.<ref>{{cite web|author=Martin, Macy Daniela|url=https://www.popsugar.com/latina/photo-gallery/38472946/video/38473138/When-Paulina-Rubio-made-her-first-appearance-show-perform-M%C3%ADo-1992 |title=The 18 Biggest S\u00e1bado Gigante Moments You'll Never Forget |work=[[PopSugar]] |date=September 20, 2015|language=English|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\n''\"La Chica Dorada\"'' was often aired on [[radio airplay]] in Mexico for two months. It, however, was only a Mexican release and was not part of her single debut project. \"M\u00edo\" was the first single from the album and featured lyrics written by [[Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n Fl\u00f3rez]]. The producer of the album, [[Miguel Blasco]], thought that Paulina should transmit a more sophisticated and sexy image, and that reflected in her debut single. It peaked number three on US [[Hot Latin Songs|Hot Latin Track]]. \"Amor De Mujer\", the second single in Latin America, reached number eight in the US Hot Latin Tracks. Rubio re-released \"Abriendo Las Puertas Al Amor\" in April 1993 in Latin America. It was released as the album's second single in US and became the highest entry of the US Latin singles chart by a female artist with the singles and debut album. \"Sabor A Miel\", the fourth single in US. \"Amarte En Libertad\" was exclusively released in Latin America as the airplay single in July, 1993 and the song was the prelude to Rubio's second album, ''[[24 Kilates]]'', which would be published only 4 months later.\n\n===Additional releases===\nThe first singles of ''La Chica Dorada'' were repackaged as a maxi-single album entitled ''Paulina Rubio'' in countries like Mexico and Ecuador in 1993, with additional mixes of the singles \"M\u00edo\" and \"Amor De Mujer\". In the Ecuador edition it was launched with the promotion of the third single from the album, \"Sabor A Miel\". The album has been digitally remastered from the original studio tapes. They were available in vinyl, 12\" and CD.<ref>{{cite web |title=Paulina Rubio (Single) |url=https://www.discogs.com/es/Paulina-Rubio-Paulina-Rubio/master/939685 |website=discogs.com |accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/la-chica-dorada-mw0000088611 |title=ALLMUSIC REVIEW: La Chica Dorada - Paulina Rubio |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |year=2006|language=|accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref>\n|rev2       = [[Apple Music]]\n|rev2Score  = favourable<ref name=\"appleinc\">{{cite web| url=https://itunes.apple.com/mx/album/la-chica-dorada/723816942 | accessdate=March 7, 2019| work=[[Apple Inc.]]| title=La Chica Dorada by Paulina Rubio on Apple Music|quote=Despu\u00e9s de Timbiriche nadie esperaba la mezcla de g\u00e9neros que presentar\u00eda Paulina Rubio...}}</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n[[File:Marilyn Monroe Niagara.png|thumb|left|190px|Many critics compare the image of ''La Chica Dorada'' with [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Marilyn Monroe]] (''picture'').]]\n\n''La Chica Dorada'' had received mixed reviews from music critics. ''[[AllMusic]]'' rateit three of five stars, giving it a mixed review and considering the album energetic, exuberant, passionate and intense like the aesthetic image and personality of Paulina Rubio.<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/la-chica-dorada-mw0000088611 |title=ALLMUSIC REVIEW: La Chica Dorada - Paulina Rubio |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |year=2006|language=|accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref> Due to the success of \"M\u00edo\", in Mexico the journalists considered her solo debut as the new \"Latin pop icon\" and a great business for her label [[Capitol Latin|EMI/Capitol Latin]].<ref name=\"HitParade\">{{cite news|url=http://h.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib:LowLevelEntityToSaveGifMSIE_ELSIGLO&Type=text/html&Locale=spanish-skin-custom&Path=EDT/1994/03/09&ChunkNum=-1&ID=Ar04300&PageLabel=43|title=Hit Parade|language=Spanish|newspaper=El Siglo de Torre\u00f3n|publisher=Editora de la Laguna|page=43|date=March 9, 1994}}</ref> ''[[Apple Music]]'' considers that [La Chica Dorada] \"is an album with a risky musical proposal that transcends\".<ref name=\"AppleMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/mx/album/la-chica-dorada/723816942 |title=Apple Music - La Chica Dorada |language=Spanish |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMany Critics could not avoid comparing ''La Chica Dorada'' to [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]<ref name=\"Paulina Rubio-influencias\">{{cite news|url=http://inflooenz.com/?artist=Paulina+Rubio|title=Influencias de Paulina Rubio|language=Spanish|newspaper=|publisher=|page=|date=2012}}</ref> dance-pop 80's era records, and to tell the truth, what makes the album distinctive is Rubio's authentic personality: sophisticated young adult and sensual, genuinely compared to [[Marilyn Monroe]]. In fact, Rubio remarked a mole on the side of the lip, like the Hollywood actress. Trapped in these stereotypes, the singer it makes its way through implacable and passionate clues such as \"M\u00edo\", \"Amarte En Libertad\", \"Amor De Mujer\" and \"Sabor A Miel\" in styles dance-pop. ''La Chica Dorada'' remains one of her defining albums of Latin pop.\n\n''[[El Pa\u00eds]]'' newspaper's Elena Reina wrote recently that \"[Rubio] turn from adolescence to the age of majority to hit new record. If her image had already been important to her career as a child, now [with her debut] it becomes crucial\", ultimately concluding that the album was her passage from girl to woman.<ref name=\"en\u00e9simo\">{{cite web|author=Reina, Elena|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/06/15/gente/1529034885_873469.html|title=El en\u00e9simo regreso de Paulina Rubio, la chica dorada\n|work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|date=June 16, 1993|language=Spanish|accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref> Catalan music critic and journalist Jordi Bianciotto categorized ''La Chica Dorada'' as \"a light and danceable pop record\" and expressed his \"disconcerting version\" of \"La Escoba\", which was originally sung by the Spanish rock group [[Los S\u00edrex]]. Similarly to most critics, he highlighted Rubio's success with his debut.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bianciotto |first1=Jordi |title=Paulina Rubio vuelve a la carga |url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/mas-periodico/20190112/paulina-rubio-la-voz-7238448 |website=elperiodico.com.es |publisher=El Peri\u00f3dico |accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''La Chica Dorada'' debuted on the USA Latin Pop Albums Chart on January 1993. In its eightth week, it peaked at number two and stayed there for two consecutive weeks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Billboard Latin Pop Albums (1993-03-19) |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/latin-pop-albums/1993-03-19 |website=www.billboard.com |publisher=billboard.com |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> Rubio became the first Mexican female artist to have a success album with her debut as solo artist on Billboard charts \u2014She was also the first member of Timbiriche who managed to enter those lists. La Chica Dorada topped the Top Latin Albums chart for two additional weeks in 27 August 1993, for a total of three weeks in the number forty-two position. It sold 100,000  in the USA, the equivalent of a gold certification. \n\nIn Rubio's native Mexico, La Chica Dorada was certified three times gold in the first five months of its launch and  the summer 1993 it was certified platinum with sales of 600,000 over the course of ten months.<ref name=\"sixhundred\"/> La Chica Dorada went on to be one of the highest-selling album of the decade\u2014by a female solo artist\u2014in Mexico and sold 1 million of copies all around the world.<ref name=\"Pau\">{{cite web |last1=Coyoli |first1=Alejandro |title=Paulina Rubio; una vida de triunfos y \u00e9xitos |url=https://www.revistacentral.com.mx/notas/noticias/326338/paulina-rubio-una-vida-de-triunfos-y-exitos |website=revistacentral.com |publisher=Revista Central |accessdate=4 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1993\n| Best Music Video for \"M\u00edo\"\n| ERES Awards\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[11th TVyNovelas Awards|1993]]\n| Female Singer Revelation of the Year<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.tapatalk.com/groups/recordaresvivir/scans-de-la-xi-entrega-de-los-premios-tvynovelas-e-t31871.html#p104234|title=Scans de la XI Entrega de los Premios TVyNovelas en 1993 (a lo mejor del 92)|publisher=tapatalk.com|year=1993|language=spanish|accessdate=November 25, 2018}}</ref>\n| [[11th TVyNovelas Awards|TVyNovelas Awards]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1993\n| Youthful Revelation of the Year<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.clubfansite.com/paulinarubio/biografia.php|title=Bio, Paulina Rubio|publisher=Fan site|year=1995|language=spanish|accessdate=April 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| [[El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Premio Lo Nuestro 1993|1993]]\n| Female Artist of the Year, Pop<ref name=\"LatinNoms-book\">{{cite book|author=Lannert, John|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0w8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA49&dq=paulina+rubio+abriendo+las+puertas+al+amor&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwibrrmEvbTgAhUG0KwKHd7jBRQQ6AEILDAA#v=onepage&q=Paulina%20Rubio&f=false |title=Secada Leads Latin Noms Following Grammy Win |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=March 13, 1993|language=English|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Lo Nuestro Awards]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Premio Lo Nuestro 1993|1993]]\n| New Pop Artist of the Year<ref name=\"LatinNoms-book\"/>\n| Lo Nuestro Awards\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1993\n| Revelation of the Year<ref name=\"Paupower-awards\">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.paupower.com/english/rubiography.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091017033322/http://www.paupower.com/english/rubiography.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 17, 2009|title=Nominations, Awards, Distinctions and Special Recognitions|publisher=paupower.com|year=2010|language=spanish|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n| Galardon a los Grandes\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1993\n| Performing<ref name=\"Paupower-awards\"/>\n| AcaFest Music Festival\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| total_length    = {{duration|m=37|s=59}}\n| title1          = [[Mio (Paulina Rubio Song)|M\u00edo]]\n| note1           =\n| writer1         = {{flatlist|\n* [[J.R. Florez]]\n* Cesar Valle\n}}\n| extra1          = {{flatlist|\n* [[J.R. Florez]]\n* [[Miguel Blasco]]\n}}\n| length1         = 3:33\n\n| title2          = Dime Si Soy Sexy\n| writer2         = {{flatlist|\n* J.R. Florez\n* Cesar Valle\n}}\n| extra2          = J.R. Florez\n| length2         = 3:56\n\n| title3          = [[Sabor a Miel|Sabor A Miel]]\n| writer3         = {{flatlist|\n* J.R. Florez\n* Cesar Valle\n}}\n| extra3          = J.R. Florez\n| length3         = 3:53\n\n| title4          = El Primer Amor\n| writer4         = [[Aleks Syntek]]\n| extra4          = Miguel Blasco\n| length4         = 4:06\n\n| title5          = [[Amor de Mujer|Amor De Mujer]]\n| writer5         = {{flatlist|\n* [[Gian Pietro Felisatti|Difelisatti]]\n* J.R. Florez\n* Cesar Valle\n}}\n| extra5          = J.R. Florez\n| length5         = 3:50\n\n| title6          = La Escoba\n| writer6         = [[Los S\u00edrex]]\n| extra6          = Miguel Blasco\n| length6         = 2:50\n\n| title7          = La Chica Dorada\n| writer7         = {{flatlist|\n* J.R. Florez\n* Cesar Valle\n* [[Paulina Rubio]]\n}}\n| extra7          = J.R. Fl\u00f3rez\n| length7         = 3:08\n\n| title8          = [[Abriendo las Puertas al Amor|Abriendo Las Puertas Al Amor]]\n| writer8         = {{flatlist|\n* Difelisatti\n* J.R. Florez\n* Cesar Valle\n}}\n| extra8          = J.R. Fl\u00f3rez\n| length8         = 4:38\n\n| title9          = Sangre Latina\n| writer9         = {{flatlist|\n* J.R. Florez\n* Cesar Valle\n}}\n| extra9          = J.R. Fl\u00f3rez\n| length9         = 4:50\n\n| title10         = Amarte En Libertad\n| writer10        = {{flatlist|\n* Difelisatti\n* J.R. Florez\n* Cesar Valle\n}}\n| extra10         = J.R. Florez\n| length10        = 3:15\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nThe following people contributed to ''La Chica Dorada'':<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.discogs.com/es/Paulina-Rubio-La-Chica-Dorada/release/9310189|title=Cr\u00e9ditos Paulina Rubio \u2013 La Chica Dorada |publisher=[[Discogs]] |year=2006|language=|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n*[[Paulina Rubio]] \u2013 lead vocals, backing vocals, main performer, songwriter\n'''Additional personnel'''\n*[[Miguel Blasco]] \u2013 [[music director]], [[executive producer]]\n*Luis M\u00e9ndez \u2013 A&E\n*Remy Causse \u2013 [[arrangement]]s\n*[[J.R. Florez]] \u2013 [[record producer]], [[composer]]\n*Cesar Valle \u2013 composer\n*[[Gian Pietro Felisatti]] \u2013 composer\n*[[Aleks Syntek]] \u2013 composer\n*Jos\u00e9 Antonio \u00c1lvarez Alija \u2013 [[Audio engineer|engineering]]\n*Carlos Latap\u00ed L \u2013 photography\n\n== Charts ==\n<!--\n\nAll chart figures have to be referenced using a reliable source. If not referenced, they will be challenged and can and will be removed by any editor. Read Wikipedia:Verifiability and Wikipedia:Cite for more information.\n\n--->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#ebf5ff\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1993)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. Latin Pop Albums (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.billboard.com/album/331661/la-chica-dorada |title=Billboard: La Chica Dorada - Paulina Rubio |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |year=2013|language=|accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardLatin|42|artist=Paulina Rubio|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certifications and sales==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n!scope=\"row\"| Guatemala<ref name=\"Gold\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S0aOrOlsM-M|title=Paulina Rubio (audio) habla del \u00e9xito de La Chica Dorada (Teletica Costa Rica, 1993)|first=|last=|date=September 15, 1993|publisher=[[Teletica]]|work=Teletica Espect\u00e1culos|accessdate=October 9, 2019|quote=Rubio talks about gold certification in the United States and Guatemala at 3:33}}</ref>\n|Gold\n|5,000\n|-\n{{certification Table Entry|region=Mexico|type=album|title=La Chica Dorada|artist=Paulina Rubio|award=Platinum+3\u00d7 Gold|certref=<ref name=\"PRlcdP\"/>|relyear=1993|salesamount=600,000|salesref=<ref name=\"sixhundred\">{{cite web |title=Paulina Ruio se separa |url=https://mx.hola.com/biografias/paulina-rubio/ |website=\u00a1Hola! |accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| United States\n|\n|100,000<ref name=\"Gold\"/>\n|-\n{{Certification Table Summary}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Worldwide\n|style=\"text-align:center\"| \u2014\n|1,000,000<ref name=\"Pau\"/>\n|-\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Release format\n! Label\n|-\n| M\u00e9xico\n| {{flatlist|\n*[[Compact disc|CD]]\n*[[LP record|LP]]\n*[[Compact cassette|Cassette]]}}\n| EMI Capitol de M\u00e9xico\n|-\n| United States<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/es/Paulina-Rubio-La-Chica-Dorada/release/9389032 \"''La Chica Dorada'' US CD album\"]. [[Discogs]]. Retrieved November 25, 2018.</ref>\n| {{flatlist|\n*[[Compact disc|CD]]\n*[[Compact cassette|Cassette]]}}\n| [[Capitol Latin|Capitol/EMI Latin]]\n|-\n| Canada<ref>[http://www.coveralia.com/discos/paulina_rubio-la_chica_dorada.php \"''La Chica Dorada'' Canada CD album\"]. Retrieved November 25, 2018.</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| CD\n| [[Capitol Records]]\n|-\n| Spain<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/es/Paulina-Rubio-La-Chica-Dorada/release/12349891 \"''La Chica Dorada'' Spain CD album\"]. [[Discogs]]. Retrieved November 25, 2018.</ref>\n| [[Virgin Records]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[1992 in Latin music]]\n*[[Honorific nicknames in popular music]]\n*[[List of artists influenced by Madonna]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{citation\n | last = Luna\n | first = Iraide\n | title = Paulina Rubio \"El Hurac\u00e1n Mexicano\"\n | year = 2001\n | publisher = Nuer Ediciones\n | isbn = 978-84-8068-079-0\n | location = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Espa\u00f1a]]\n }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Discogs master|503859|La Chica Dorada}}\n\n{{Paulina Rubio}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chica Dorada}}\n[[Category:1992 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Paulina Rubio albums]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language albums]]\n[[Category:EMI Latin albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = La Chica Dorada\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Paulina Rubio]]\n| cover      = PAU El tiempo es oro`.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1992|10|20|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = December 1991&nbsp;\u2013 February 1992\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Balu-Balu Estudios<br />([[Madrid]], [[Spain]])\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Latin pop]]|[[dance pop]]}}\n| length     = 37:59\n| label      = [[Capitol Latin]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Miguel Blasco]]|[[J.R. Florez]]}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[24 Kilates]]\n| next_year  = 1993\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = La Chica Dorada\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[M\u00edo]]\n | single1date = {{Start date|1992|8|30|mf=y}}\n | single2     = [[Abriendo las Puertas al Amor|Abriendo Las Puertas Al Amor]]\n | single2date = {{Start date|1993|2|20|mf=y}}\n | single3     = [[Amor de Mujer|Amor De Mujer]]\n | single3date = {{Start date|1993|5|29|mf=y}}\n | single4     = [[Sabor a Miel|Sabor A Miel]]\n | single4date = {{Start date|1993|8|12|mf=y}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''La Chica Dorada''''' (English: ''The Golden Girl'') is the solo debut studio album by Mexican pop singer [[Paulina Rubio]] (after leaving the [[Timbiriche]] group) and her first album by the [[EMI Latin]] record label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paulinarubio.com/site/listDiscography/xn/Discografia/_lang/es_ES/id/7/title/la-chica-dorada|title=Paulina Rubio Official Website: Discography -La Chica Dorada|publisher=paulinarubio.com|year=2012|accessdate=February 16, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426091110/http://www.paulinarubio.com/site/listDiscography/xn/Discografia/_lang/es_ES/id/7/title/la-chica-dorada|archivedate=April 26, 2012}}</ref> The album was produced and directed by [[Miguel Blasco]], and written mostly by [[J.R. Florez]], [[Gian Pietro Felisatti]] and Cesar Valle. Most of the composition of the album is [[dance-pop]], although it includes some elements of [[rock pop]], [[new jack swing]], [[new wave]] and [[funk]].\n\nThe album has received a mixed review from music critics; Many medios applauded the album itself for interesting themes and her step in the music industry as \"the girl to woman\", while some did not like another \"[[Madonna wannabe]]\" because of the great influence of the [[Madonna (entertainer)|North American artist]] on the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/cultura/paulina-rubio-dice-que-es-un-orgullo-que-la-califiquen-como-la-madonna/2001-09-09/105000.html|title=Paulina Rubio dice que es un orgullo que la califiquen como la \"Madonna latina\"|publisher=|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref> Despite the mixed critical reaction, ''La Chica Dorada'' was a worldwide success. The album includes Rubio's [[signature song]] and the single that launched her solo career, \"[[Mio (Paulina Rubio Song)|M\u00edo]]\", along with the number one hit singles \"[[Sabor a Miel|Sabor A Miel]]\" and \"[[Amor de Mujer|Amor De Mujer]]\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Paulina Rubio conducir\u00e1 ceremonia de MTV Video Music Awards |url=https://hoy.com.do/paulina-rubio-conducira-ceremonia-de-mtv-video-music-awards/ |website=hoydigital.do |publisher=Hoy Digital |accessdate=8 October 2019 |date=15 September 2004}}</ref> The album's title has stuck and today Rubio is known as 'la chica dorada' (the golden girl) and throughout the Spanish-speaking world. In Mexico, it was certifield platinum and three times gold in the 90s<ref name=\"PRlcdP\">{{cite web |title=Hit Parade |url=http://h.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Search&Key=EDT/1993/03/02/43/Ar04300.xml&CollName=EDT_1990_1999&DOCID=1226315&PageLabelPrint=43&skin=ElSiglo&AppName=2&sLanguage=English&Content=ALL&selLanguage=&sPublication=EDT&sDateFrom=01/01/1993&sDateTo=12/31/1993&dummy=1993&sQuery=paulina+rubio+platino&x=0&y=0&ViewMode=GIF |date=March 2, 1993 |accessdate=November 2, 2019 |work=[[El Siglo de Torre\u00f3n]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102165853/http://h.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Search&Key=EDT%2F1993%2F03%2F02%2F43%2FAr04300.xml&CollName=EDT_1990_1999&DOCID=1226315&PageLabelPrint=43&skin=ElSiglo&AppName=2&sLanguage=English&Content=ALL&selLanguage=&sPublication=EDT&sDateFrom=01%2F01%2F1993&sDateTo=12%2F31%2F1993&dummy=1993&sQuery=paulina+rubio+platino&x=0&y=0&ViewMode=GIF |archivedate=November 2, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and sold over 600,000 copies.<ref name=\"sixhundred\"/>\n\nIn the [[United States]], ''La Chica Dorada'' peaked at No. 42 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Top Latin Albums]] and sold 100,000 copies. The singles \"M\u00edo\", \"Amor De Mujer\" and \"[[Abriendo las puertas al amor|Abriendo Las Puertas Al Amor]]\" entered the Top 10 of [[Hot Latin Tracks]], turning Paulina Rubio into a strong promise of Hispanic music,<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0w8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA85&dq=paulina+rubio+la+chica+dorada&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiB8eyDjPXdAhVFIqwKHbBoCGYQ6AEILjAB#v=onepage&q=paulina%20rubio%20la%20chica%20dorada&f=false |title=Magic's In The Music And The Music's In These |publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=March 13, 1993|language=|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref> and the first Mexican artist who managed to enter the most important list of the music industry with her debut album, after the first releases of [[Ana Gabriel]], who had great success on the ''Billboard Latin'' charts.\n\n==Background and development==\n{{Quote box|width=300px|bgcolor=#cd9c3a|align=left|quote=\"For me the gold are memories: the golden years of rock and roll and cinema.\"|source=\u2014Rubio talking about the name of the album.\n}}\nAfter having been part of the [[Timbiriche]] group and recording ten studio albums, Rubio traveled to Europe in 1991 to study History of Art, but his greatest wish was to start his solo career. This is how [[Gian Pietro Felisatti]], better known as \"DiFelisatti\", one of the most outstanding composers of that era, along with [[Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n Fl\u00f3rez]], volunteered to work on the solo project of the young artist of 20 years. The well-known producers and she had a very good relationship, since both writers were responsible for great successes of the band Timbiriche. Added to the above, Rubio was established in Spain to start recordings of what would be his debut album.\n\n[[Miguel Blasco]], Spanish producer of the greatest discographic hits of [[Alejandra Guzm\u00e1n]], [[Yuri (Mexican singer)|Yuri]] and [[Mijares]] would handle all the production of La Chica Dorada, achieving a breakthrough in just four months of work. In June 1992, Paulina Rubio officially signed a contract with the [[EMI Latin|EMI Capitol]] label in Mexico<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubfansite.com/paulinarubio/biografia.php|title=Paulina Rubio, Biography|publisher=Fan site|year=1995|language=Spanish|accessdate=April 14, 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414145859/http://www.clubfansite.com/paulinarubio/biografia.php|archivedate=April 14, 2019}}</ref> and the song \"La Chica Dorada\" was released exclusively to publicize her solo project. The song describes the moments Rubio lived in Spain while studying Art History and dreamed of becoming a Hispanic pop star.\n\n==Released and promotion==\n[[File:EroticaGirlieShowUnderGround sh (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|\"La Chica Dorada\" was released the same day that [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], one of her biggest influences, published her album \"[[Erotica (Madonna album)|Erotica]]\".]]\n\nPrior to the promotion of the album, Rubio gave several details of his solo debut while he was recording the last scenes of the telenovela ''[[Baila conmigo (TV series)|Baila conmigo]]'', informing the media of his great radical change of image. ''La Chica Dorada'' was released in Mexico and United States on October 20, 1992, the same day that Madonna released her fifth studio album, ''[[Erotica (Madonna album)|Erotica]]''. The album was re-released in [[Europe]] in 2001, and the digital edition was released in 2005.\n\nThe promotion began in July 1992, when Rubio conducted a small advertising campaign by several Mexican media outlets, where she presented her new image as \"golden girl\" and promoted the song \"La Chica Dorada\" on some radio stations. \" The singer made several promotional appearances, including talk shows and live performances in the main cities of Mexico. Paulina Rubio made her debut as a solo singer on the legendary Mexican television program [[Siempre en Domingo]], with [[Ra\u00fal Velasco]] on October 18, 1992,<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1612204/ |title=Debut de Paulina Rubio como solista  |work=[[IMDb]] |year=2012|language=english |accessdate=October 12, 2018}}</ref> 3 days before her album was released. She performed the song \"Amor De Mujer\" and her first single, \"M\u00edo\". The famous television host commented that \"it was a great privilege to have presented Paulina as a solo singer\". His presentation had a high audience rating that the next week was invited again.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TZ9oz49bSuw |title=Paulina Rubio debut como solista en Siempre en Domingo |work=[[YouTube]] |year=2015|language=spanish|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref> In United States, for the Spanish-language television program [[S\u00e1bado Gigante]], Rubio performed the track \"M\u00edo\" in January, 1993 and that presentation opened the doors to the Hispanic market in that country.<ref>{{cite web|author=Martin, Macy Daniela|url=https://www.popsugar.com/latina/photo-gallery/38472946/video/38473138/When-Paulina-Rubio-made-her-first-appearance-show-perform-M%C3%ADo-1992 |title=The 18 Biggest S\u00e1bado Gigante Moments You'll Never Forget |work=[[PopSugar]] |date=September 20, 2015|language=English|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\n''\"La Chica Dorada\"'' was often aired on [[radio airplay]] in Mexico for two months. It, however, was only a Mexican release and was not part of her single debut project. \"M\u00edo\" was the first single from the album and featured lyrics written by [[Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00f3n Fl\u00f3rez]]. The producer of the album, [[Miguel Blasco]], thought that Paulina should transmit a more sophisticated and sexy image, and that reflected in her debut single. It peaked number three on US [[Hot Latin Songs|Hot Latin Track]]. \"Amor De Mujer\", the second single in Latin America, reached number eight in the US Hot Latin Tracks. Rubio re-released \"Abriendo Las Puertas Al Amor\" in April 1993 in Latin America. It was released as the album's second single in US and became the highest entry of the US Latin singles chart by a female artist with the singles and debut album. \"Sabor A Miel\", the fourth single in US. \"Amarte En Libertad\" was exclusively released in Latin America as the airplay single in July, 1993 and the song was the prelude to Rubio's second album, ''[[24 Kilates]]'', which would be published only 4 months later.\n\n===Additional releases===\nThe first singles of ''La Chica Dorada'' were repackaged as a maxi-single album entitled ''Paulina Rubio'' in countries like Mexico and Ecuador in 1993, with additional mixes of the singles \"M\u00edo\" and \"Amor De Mujer\". In the Ecuador edition it was launched with the promotion of the third single from the album, \"Sabor A Miel\". The album has been digitally remastered from the original studio tapes. They were available in vinyl, 12\" and CD.<ref>{{cite web |title=Paulina Rubio (Single) |url=https://www.discogs.com/es/Paulina-Rubio-Paulina-Rubio/master/939685 |website=discogs.com |accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/la-chica-dorada-mw0000088611 |title=ALLMUSIC REVIEW: La Chica Dorada - Paulina Rubio |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |year=2006|language=|accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref>\n|rev2       = [[Apple Music]]\n|rev2Score  = favourable<ref name=\"appleinc\">{{cite web| url=https://itunes.apple.com/mx/album/la-chica-dorada/723816942 | accessdate=March 7, 2019| work=[[Apple Inc.]]| title=La Chica Dorada by Paulina Rubio on Apple Music|quote=Despu\u00e9s de Timbiriche nadie esperaba la mezcla de g\u00e9neros que presentar\u00eda Paulina Rubio...}}</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n[[File:Marilyn Monroe Niagara.png|thumb|left|190px|Many critics compare the image of ''La Chica Dorada'' with [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Marilyn Monroe]] (''picture'').]]\n\n''La Chica Dorada'' had received mixed reviews from music critics. ''[[AllMusic]]'' rateit three of five stars, giving it a mixed review and considering the album energetic, exuberant, passionate and intense like the aesthetic image and personality of Paulina Rubio.<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/la-chica-dorada-mw0000088611 |title=ALLMUSIC REVIEW: La Chica Dorada - Paulina Rubio |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |year=2006|language=|accessdate=February 16, 2013}}</ref> Due to the success of \"M\u00edo\", in Mexico the journalists considered her solo debut as the new \"Latin pop icon\" and a great business for her label [[Capitol Latin|EMI/Capitol Latin]].<ref name=\"HitParade\">{{cite news|url=http://h.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib:LowLevelEntityToSaveGifMSIE_ELSIGLO&Type=text/html&Locale=spanish-skin-custom&Path=EDT/1994/03/09&ChunkNum=-1&ID=Ar04300&PageLabel=43|title=Hit Parade|language=Spanish|newspaper=El Siglo de Torre\u00f3n|publisher=Editora de la Laguna|page=43|date=March 9, 1994}}</ref> ''[[Apple Music]]'' considers that [La Chica Dorada] \"is an album with a risky musical proposal that transcends\".<ref name=\"AppleMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/mx/album/la-chica-dorada/723816942 |title=Apple Music - La Chica Dorada |language=Spanish |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMany Critics could not avoid comparing ''La Chica Dorada'' to [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]<ref name=\"Paulina Rubio-influencias\">{{cite news|url=http://inflooenz.com/?artist=Paulina+Rubio|title=Influencias de Paulina Rubio|language=Spanish|newspaper=|publisher=|page=|date=2012}}</ref> dance-pop 80's era records, and to tell the truth, what makes the album distinctive is Rubio's authentic personality: sophisticated young adult and sensual, genuinely compared to [[Marilyn Monroe]]. In fact, Rubio remarked a mole on the side of the lip, like the Hollywood actress. Trapped in these stereotypes, the singer it makes its way through implacable and passionate clues such as \"M\u00edo\", \"Amarte En Libertad\", \"Amor De Mujer\" and \"Sabor A Miel\" in styles dance-pop. ''La Chica Dorada'' remains one of her defining albums of Latin pop.\n\n''[[El Pa\u00eds]]'' newspaper's Elena Reina wrote recently that \"[Rubio] turn from adolescence to the age of majority to hit new record. If her image had already been important to her career as a child, now [with her debut] it becomes crucial\", ultimately concluding that the album was her passage from girl to woman.<ref name=\"en\u00e9simo\">{{cite web|author=Reina, Elena|url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/06/15/gente/1529034885_873469.html|title=El en\u00e9simo regreso de Paulina Rubio, la chica dorada\n|work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|date=June 16, 1993|language=Spanish|accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref> Catalan music critic and journalist Jordi Bianciotto categorized ''La Chica Dorada'' as \"a light and danceable pop record\" and expressed his \"disconcerting version\" of \"La Escoba\", which was originally sung by the Spanish rock group [[Los S\u00edrex]]. Similarly to most critics, he highlighted Rubio's success with his debut.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bianciotto |first1=Jordi |title=Paulina Rubio vuelve a la carga |url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/mas-periodico/20190112/paulina-rubio-la-voz-7238448 |website=elperiodico.com.es |publisher=El Peri\u00f3dico |accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''La Chica Dorada'' debuted on the USA Latin Pop Albums Chart on January 1993. In its eightth week, it peaked at number two and stayed there for two consecutive weeks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Billboard Latin Pop Albums (1993-03-19) |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/latin-pop-albums/1993-03-19 |website=www.billboard.com |publisher=billboard.com |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> Rubio became the first Mexican female artist to have a success album with her debut as solo artist on Billboard charts \u2014She was also the first member of Timbiriche who managed to enter those lists. La Chica Dorada topped the Top Latin Albums chart for two additional weeks in 27 August 1993, for a total of three weeks in the number fourty-two position. It sold 100,000  in the USA, the equivalent of a gold certification. \n\nIn Rubio's native Mexico, La Chica Dorada was certified three times gold in the first five months of its launch and  the summer 1993 it was certified platinum with sales of 600,000 over the course of ten months.<ref name=\"sixhundred\"/> La Chica Dorada went on to be one of the highest-selling album of the decade\u2014by a female solo artist\u2014in Mexico and sold 1 million of copies all around the world.<ref name=\"Pau\">{{cite web |last1=Coyoli |first1=Alejandro |title=Paulina Rubio; una vida de triunfos y \u00e9xitos |url=https://www.revistacentral.com.mx/notas/noticias/326338/paulina-rubio-una-vida-de-triunfos-y-exitos |website=revistacentral.com |publisher=Revista Central |accessdate=4 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1993\n| Best Music Video for \"M\u00edo\"\n| ERES Awards\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[11th TVyNovelas Awards|1993]]\n| Female Singer Revelation of the Year<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.tapatalk.com/groups/recordaresvivir/scans-de-la-xi-entrega-de-los-premios-tvynovelas-e-t31871.html#p104234|title=Scans de la XI Entrega de los Premios TVyNovelas en 1993 (a lo mejor del 92)|publisher=tapatalk.com|year=1993|language=spanish|accessdate=November 25, 2018}}</ref>\n| [[11th TVyNovelas Awards|TVyNovelas Awards]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1993\n| Youthful Revelation of the Year<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.clubfansite.com/paulinarubio/biografia.php|title=Bio, Paulina Rubio|publisher=Fan site|year=1995|language=spanish|accessdate=April 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| [[El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Premio Lo Nuestro 1993|1993]]\n| Female Artist of the Year, Pop<ref name=\"LatinNoms-book\">{{cite book|author=Lannert, John|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0w8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA49&dq=paulina+rubio+abriendo+las+puertas+al+amor&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwibrrmEvbTgAhUG0KwKHd7jBRQQ6AEILDAA#v=onepage&q=Paulina%20Rubio&f=false |title=Secada Leads Latin Noms Following Grammy Win |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=March 13, 1993|language=English|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Lo Nuestro Awards]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Premio Lo Nuestro 1993|1993]]\n| New Pop Artist of the Year<ref name=\"LatinNoms-book\"/>\n| Lo Nuestro Awards\n| 